WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.980 --> 00:00:04.660
Hi, everybody. I'm Marika Speranza, and I'm a

2
00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:08.600
GSK employee. And I'm here on behalf of GSK to

3
00:00:09.060 --> 00:00:12.690
introduce the AACR-GSK Gertrude Elion

4
00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:16.160
Gertrude Award. Gertrude Elion was a pioneer

5
00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:19.200
biochemist and pharmacologist whose background work

6
00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:22.510
revolutionized modern medicine and drug discovery.

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.940
While at Burnham Welcome, that is one of GSK legacy company, she developed

8
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.820
some of the first effective therapeutics for leukemia and other cancers,

9
00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:35.280
as well as antivirals that transformed the treatment of infection disease.

10
00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:39.200
Remarkably, she achieved those milestones at a time

11
00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:43.200
where women were rarely seen, and let alone welcome in the

12
00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:45.260
laboratory. So that was very remarkable.

13
00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:48.580
Her discovery changed the life of millions of patients.

14
00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:52.700
And that's not only earned a Nobel Prize in 1988,

15
00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:57.000
but it also fundamentally shaped our understanding of

16
00:00:57.020 --> 00:00:59.800
rational mechanism-based drug design.

17
00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:04.320
The Gertrude Elion Award celebrate this legacy by

18
00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:08.260
supporting exceptionally early career investigators who continue to

19
00:01:08.300 --> 00:01:10.960
push the boundaries for cancer research.

20
00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:15.300
So this year, it is my very honor and pleasure to introduce our

21
00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:19.340
speaker, Dr. Carmen Li. Dr. Carmen is an assistant professor of

22
00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:23.240
cancer biology at the University of Pennsylvania, and a core investigator

23
00:01:23.300 --> 00:01:27.000
of the Basser Center for BRCA. She earned her AB

24
00:01:27.180 --> 00:01:31.100
from Princeton University and then moved to MIT

25
00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:35.000
for a PhD. She continued her postdoc work at the

26
00:01:35.020 --> 00:01:38.720
Harvard Medical School, focusing of memory cell state plasticity

27
00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:41.920
under genetic and physiological cancer risk factors.

28
00:01:42.450 --> 00:01:46.170
Her lab at UPenn investigate the driving mechanism and

29
00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:50.040
targetable vulnerability of hereditary cancers, as

30
00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:53.940
well as the implication for sporadic cancers by combining

31
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.020
genetic mouse models, organoids, and genomic tools.

32
00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:01.360
Please join me in welcoming Dr. Carmen Li, who will deliver a

33
00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.180
lecture entitled, "Harness Insight from Chromatin Priming

34
00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:08.700
from Early Interception of Basal Like Breast Cancer."

35
00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:16.800
Hi, everyone, and thank you, Dr. Speranza, for the very kind

36
00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.780
introduction. I'm deeply honored and humbled to be selected by

37
00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.180
the AACR for the Gertrude B. Elion Award for Cancer Research.

38
00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:28.540
And to get this recognition and support for a new investigator

39
00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:29.620
like me and my lab,

40
00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:34.660
I'm incredibly grateful. And thank you for the AACR for

41
00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:38.660
supporting young labs like ours. And so today, I'm very excited

42
00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:42.060
to share ongoing work in our lab supported by this award.

43
00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:47.680
As Dr. Speranza mentioned, I'm a new assistant professor

44
00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:51.120
in the Department of Cancer Biology at the University of Pennsylvania,

45
00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:54.100
and I started my lab about a year ago.

46
00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:57.960
We're broadly interested in studying the development of hereditary

47
00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:01.560
cancer that's driven by inherited

48
00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.360
mutations in various tumor suppressor genes that can

49
00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:09.160
give to substantially elevated risks of cancer development in different

50
00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:13.180
tissue types. We study that both under baseline condition as well as

51
00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:17.230
under physiological stress, such as with pregnancy,

52
00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:21.100
obesity, and aging. And our central goals are to

53
00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:24.720
uncover mechanistic drivers for the early onset of these

54
00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.640
diseases, as well as to identify opportunities for early detection

55
00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:32.380
and early intervention. And we believe that the

56
00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:35.820
insights coming from these hereditary diseases have important

57
00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:39.520
implications for the parallel early drivers in the

58
00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:43.549
sporadic form of the same cancer type, given the high degree of molecular

59
00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:47.560
similarity between the sporadic and hereditary forms of the same cancer type.

60
00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:52.100
And so, central to our approach is to use precisely

61
00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:56.080
designed, genetically engineered mouse models to mimic the

62
00:03:56.100 --> 00:04:00.020
germline heterozygous state of the disease, and also to capture

63
00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:00.920
the very early

64
00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:02.980
stage of the

65
00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:06.800
cancer development in a physiological and tractable manner.

66
00:04:07.780 --> 00:04:11.360
And this approach largely stems from my graduate training, with Dr.

67
00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:14.840
Tyler Jacks at MIT, to use mouse models for cancer studies.

68
00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:18.500
And that inspired me to develop a new mouse model,

69
00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:22.880
to study BRCA1-associated hereditary breast cancer.

70
00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:27.039
That's back when I was a postdoc with Dr.

71
00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:30.820
Joan Brugge at Harvard Medical School, and that became a focus of my lab

72
00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:34.680
today, which I'm very excited to talk about how we use this new mouse

73
00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:38.360
model to uncover interesting and unexpected chromatin

74
00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:42.260
changes that's associated with higher cancer

75
00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:45.000
risk and early onset of this hereditary cancer type.

76
00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:50.200
And so, by way of introduction, we know that BRCA1 is

77
00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:53.600
an important tumor suppressor gene that plays a major role in

78
00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:56.780
maintaining genome integrity by repairing DNA

79
00:04:56.820 --> 00:05:00.630
damage. And women and men who are born with a single inactivating

80
00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:04.340
mutation of BRCA1 have much higher risk of

81
00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:08.240
developing breast cancer, up to 80% chance in their

82
00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:11.860
lifetime in women mutation carriers, compared to the general

83
00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:15.540
population of non-carriers at about 13%

84
00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:16.360
lifetime risks.

85
00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:21.260
In addition to that, the age of cancer onset also tends to be much

86
00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:23.640
earlier, by about one to two decades.

87
00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:27.920
So this high degree of cancer predisposition is usually

88
00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:31.900
explained by the two hit hypothesis that's initially proposed

89
00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:35.670
by Dr. Alfred Knudson in the 1970s, which describes

90
00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:39.540
that carriers of germline mutations in

91
00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:41.830
tumor suppressor genes like BRCA1,

92
00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:46.620
they're only one more hit away or one more mutation away from full gene

93
00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.060
loss, compared to non-carriers, where two

94
00:05:50.860 --> 00:05:54.660
functional copies of the gene have to be inactivated in the

95
00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:57.960
same cell in order for cancer to develop, which is a much

96
00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:02.508
more rare event.And so this probabilistic model

97
00:06:02.588 --> 00:06:06.078
is intuitive, is elegant, is certainly not

98
00:06:06.088 --> 00:06:09.878
wrong. But I was interested in asking if there is

99
00:06:09.968 --> 00:06:13.668
any additional non-mutually exclusive explanation for this

100
00:06:13.828 --> 00:06:16.408
high degree of cancer predisposition.

101
00:06:16.948 --> 00:06:20.568
And so to directly ask this question, I developed a new mouse

102
00:06:20.668 --> 00:06:21.688
model to

103
00:06:22.768 --> 00:06:26.538
mimic the BRCA1 drumline heterozygous state in the

104
00:06:26.608 --> 00:06:29.768
mammary gland. And we did this with the help of the late Dr.

105
00:06:29.968 --> 00:06:33.708
David Livingston at Dana-Farber, and his postdoc at the time, Shailja

106
00:06:33.748 --> 00:06:36.147
Pathania, who is now at UMass Boston.

107
00:06:36.748 --> 00:06:40.568
So these heterozygous mice are born with a single inactivating mutation of

108
00:06:40.628 --> 00:06:44.598
BRCA1 that is paired with a wild-type allele that is fully

109
00:06:44.628 --> 00:06:48.458
functional. But we can later on delete that with the Cre recombinase

110
00:06:49.248 --> 00:06:52.568
shown here. And these heterozygous mice for hereditary

111
00:06:52.608 --> 00:06:56.188
cancer are compared to a wild-type model for sporadic breast

112
00:06:56.268 --> 00:07:00.028
cancer, where both copies of BRCA1 are conditionally

113
00:07:00.108 --> 00:07:02.388
wild type until Cre deletion.

114
00:07:03.448 --> 00:07:06.988
Now these mice, even including the heterozygous mice, they don't

115
00:07:07.028 --> 00:07:10.448
spontaneously develop mammary tumors, and in fact, their mammary

116
00:07:10.788 --> 00:07:12.788
gland histology look completely normal,

117
00:07:13.648 --> 00:07:17.268
just like what would you expect in human mutation carriers

118
00:07:17.528 --> 00:07:19.388
compared to non-carriers breast tissues.

119
00:07:20.028 --> 00:07:23.808
But we can inject their mammary gland with a lentivirus expressing the Cre

120
00:07:23.848 --> 00:07:27.148
recombinase, which can then convert the

121
00:07:27.248 --> 00:07:28.188
BRCA1

122
00:07:29.008 --> 00:07:29.808
flox alleles into

123
00:07:30.988 --> 00:07:34.918
null alleles, and therefore delete BRCA1 completely, either in

124
00:07:34.968 --> 00:07:37.798
the wild-type background or a heterozygous background.

125
00:07:38.508 --> 00:07:42.228
And doing so, in combination with deletion of p53, which

126
00:07:42.308 --> 00:07:45.998
is frequently co-mutated with BRCA1 in human breast cancer,

127
00:07:46.648 --> 00:07:50.388
we can develop tumors, mammary tumors, both in the

128
00:07:50.428 --> 00:07:54.188
wild type and heterozygous background mice, and specifically

129
00:07:54.248 --> 00:07:57.898
the basal subtype of breast cancer, which is associated with

130
00:07:57.948 --> 00:08:01.158
human BRCA1 somatic or

131
00:08:01.788 --> 00:08:05.368
drumline mutation, and it's a type of breast cancer that is very

132
00:08:05.448 --> 00:08:07.868
aggressive and very difficult to treat in patients.

133
00:08:09.088 --> 00:08:12.988
And so with this, we can ask the question, now that we can concurrently

134
00:08:13.048 --> 00:08:16.828
inactivate BRCA1, both in the wild type and heterozygous

135
00:08:16.848 --> 00:08:17.278
condition,

136
00:08:18.088 --> 00:08:18.778
or background,

137
00:08:19.808 --> 00:08:23.708
do these two types of mice develop tumors at the same time,

138
00:08:24.128 --> 00:08:26.678
which will be the prediction of the two-hit hypothesis?

139
00:08:27.748 --> 00:08:28.408
Interestingly, we

140
00:08:29.508 --> 00:08:33.389
saw something very different. We saw that the heterozygous mice shown

141
00:08:33.428 --> 00:08:37.328
here in orange, formed tumors earlier than the wild-type mice by

142
00:08:37.408 --> 00:08:41.249
about 20 weeks ahead. And that's also true in a different mouse

143
00:08:41.288 --> 00:08:45.048
model where we additionally target PTEN by using

144
00:08:45.088 --> 00:08:49.028
CRISPR-Cas9, both in the lenti-Cre virus and the drumline of the mice.

145
00:08:49.548 --> 00:08:53.248
And again, here, the heterozygous mice as a group developed

146
00:08:53.268 --> 00:08:55.068
tumors earlier than the wild-type mice.

147
00:08:55.828 --> 00:08:59.508
And these results are certainly unexpected according to the prediction of the

148
00:08:59.568 --> 00:09:00.608
two-hit hypothesis,

149
00:09:01.468 --> 00:09:05.168
and we have ruled out the trivial explanation that this difference, this

150
00:09:05.208 --> 00:09:08.948
delay in tumor latency, is simply because

151
00:09:09.048 --> 00:09:12.908
of a lower efficiency of the Cre recombinase to delete

152
00:09:12.917 --> 00:09:16.798
two copies of BRCA1 in the wild-type background versus just

153
00:09:16.848 --> 00:09:19.228
one copy in the heterozygous background.

154
00:09:19.248 --> 00:09:23.088
In fact, we found that the Cre is highly efficient in deleting all the conditional

155
00:09:23.128 --> 00:09:26.448
alleles in as early as four days after infection.

156
00:09:27.038 --> 00:09:31.028
And so instead, our data suggests that there are intrinsic aberrations in

157
00:09:31.048 --> 00:09:34.968
the heterozygous mammary gland that act independent from the

158
00:09:35.028 --> 00:09:38.168
timing of full BRCA1 loss to promote cancer development.

159
00:09:39.158 --> 00:09:42.968
And so we set off to look for this aberration, the

160
00:09:43.008 --> 00:09:46.568
nature of this aberration or gene haploinsufficiency effect that

161
00:09:46.648 --> 00:09:50.548
act in the heterozygous mammary gland independent from the timing

162
00:09:50.648 --> 00:09:54.488
of BRCA1 full inactivation to accelerate cancer

163
00:09:54.528 --> 00:09:58.428
development. And we've explored different directions based on

164
00:09:58.488 --> 00:10:01.428
many interesting and exciting reports in the literature,

165
00:10:02.308 --> 00:10:06.068
including gene expression changes in the epithelial or stromal

166
00:10:06.108 --> 00:10:09.908
populations within the breast, or expansion of different cell

167
00:10:09.928 --> 00:10:13.588
populations and signs of accumulated DNA damage.

168
00:10:14.068 --> 00:10:17.808
But, in our system, what jumped out most strikingly was

169
00:10:18.228 --> 00:10:21.288
chromatin accessibility changes in the mammary gland,

170
00:10:21.688 --> 00:10:25.348
specifically in a type of epithelial cells called

171
00:10:25.448 --> 00:10:29.128
secretory alveolar cells or AB cells, also

172
00:10:29.168 --> 00:10:32.408
sometimes known as luminal progenitor cells or LAP cells,

173
00:10:32.808 --> 00:10:35.708
that in the normal breast give rise to

174
00:10:35.728 --> 00:10:39.288
the cells responsible for milk

175
00:10:39.308 --> 00:10:42.978
production. And in the case of breast cancer, they are known as

176
00:10:43.028 --> 00:10:46.718
the tumor cells of origin for basal-like breast cancer, based on

177
00:10:46.808 --> 00:10:48.118
various human and mouse studies.

178
00:10:49.028 --> 00:10:52.988
So when we performed ATAC-seq chromatin accessibility profiling

179
00:10:53.468 --> 00:10:57.388
of these alveolar cells or AB cells derived from wild

180
00:10:57.468 --> 00:11:01.218
type or heterozygous mice that are completely normal and

181
00:11:01.268 --> 00:11:05.108
non-tumor bearing, they've never seen Cre-induced tumors, we

182
00:11:05.168 --> 00:11:08.588
found that these AB cells, the heterozygous AB cells,

183
00:11:09.028 --> 00:11:12.968
formed two distinct clusters based on global analysis of

184
00:11:13.008 --> 00:11:15.048
their chromatin accessibility landscape.

185
00:11:15.728 --> 00:11:19.668
Some of these heterozygous AB cells cluster with all the wild-type AB

186
00:11:19.768 --> 00:11:23.528
cells that are shown here in blue, suggesting that these are wild type-like.

187
00:11:24.128 --> 00:11:27.718
But other heterozygous AB cells form a different cluster,

188
00:11:28.048 --> 00:11:31.448
shown here as group two, suggesting that they have an altered

189
00:11:31.848 --> 00:11:35.248
chromatin state. And interestingly, these group two

190
00:11:35.328 --> 00:11:38.988
heterozygous AB cells aligned more closely with the

191
00:11:39.048 --> 00:11:42.828
tumor samples, what I'll call group three, that are derived

192
00:11:42.908 --> 00:11:46.488
from a different cohort of mice that have now been injected with

193
00:11:46.508 --> 00:11:48.688
Cre to induce mammary tumors,

194
00:11:49.588 --> 00:11:53.208
suggesting that these group two heterozygous AB cells are more

195
00:11:53.268 --> 00:11:53.988
cancer-like.

196
00:11:55.288 --> 00:11:58.908
And so further differential analysis of the chromatin accessibility data

197
00:11:59.348 --> 00:12:02.108
revealed a unique set of chromatin regions

198
00:12:03.128 --> 00:12:06.988
that showed an intermediate state of accessibility in these group two

199
00:12:07.148 --> 00:12:11.028
heterozygous AB cells relative to the group one wild type-like

200
00:12:11.088 --> 00:12:14.808
AB cells and the group three tumor cells with a pattern of

201
00:12:14.868 --> 00:12:18.828
progressively increasing level of accessibility from group one, through

202
00:12:18.848 --> 00:12:21.418
group two, to group three.And that's our

203
00:12:22.738 --> 00:12:26.378
findings in ATAC-seq data. We also looked for

204
00:12:26.678 --> 00:12:29.918
gene expression by single-cell RNA sequencing in the

205
00:12:29.978 --> 00:12:33.838
tumors developing in the wild type for Brca1 heterozygous

206
00:12:33.918 --> 00:12:37.908
background compared to normal AV cells in

207
00:12:37.938 --> 00:12:40.718
young and aged mice of the two genotypes.

208
00:12:40.728 --> 00:12:44.538
And we found that interestingly, many of the genes associated with these altered

209
00:12:44.558 --> 00:12:48.438
chromatin regions indeed show concordant increase in gene

210
00:12:48.498 --> 00:12:52.158
expression in the tumor cells, even though their expression remains

211
00:12:52.198 --> 00:12:55.978
unchanged within the normal AV cells at young age or

212
00:12:56.138 --> 00:12:59.948
old age across the two genotypes. And that's very interesting to

213
00:13:00.018 --> 00:13:01.438
us and suggests that these

214
00:13:03.038 --> 00:13:06.998
genes and chromatin regions could be primed epigenetically to

215
00:13:07.058 --> 00:13:10.698
mimic the gene activation later on happening in the tumor

216
00:13:10.818 --> 00:13:13.838
cells. But this priming already occurred in the normal

217
00:13:14.358 --> 00:13:18.178
heterozygous AV cells before Brca1 is lost and before

218
00:13:18.198 --> 00:13:19.058
tumors are formed.

219
00:13:20.978 --> 00:13:24.778
And so our findings suggest that there is an expanded view

220
00:13:24.838 --> 00:13:28.598
for the mechanism for early disease onset in the

221
00:13:28.638 --> 00:13:32.358
Brca1 heterozygous state to accelerate cancer

222
00:13:32.368 --> 00:13:35.908
development. We think that the heterozygous epithelial cells,

223
00:13:36.338 --> 00:13:39.988
specifically the alveolar cells, contain open chromatin regions

224
00:13:40.318 --> 00:13:43.978
that are distinct from the wild-type AV cells and are partially

225
00:13:44.118 --> 00:13:47.658
mimicking the chromatin state in the tumor cells, such that

226
00:13:48.698 --> 00:13:48.708
it

227
00:13:48.738 --> 00:13:53.138
primes

228
00:13:53.158 --> 00:13:56.458
for genes that can promote cancer formation and drive cancer

229
00:13:56.538 --> 00:13:59.758
development at the early stage of disease formation.

230
00:14:00.458 --> 00:14:04.098
And so this model immediately brought up a

231
00:14:04.158 --> 00:14:07.508
question which is, can these open chromatin regions

232
00:14:07.858 --> 00:14:11.598
reveal to us specific transcription factors as well as their

233
00:14:11.618 --> 00:14:15.578
gene activation programs that can take advantage of these chromatin

234
00:14:15.658 --> 00:14:19.178
changes, and drive the expression of

235
00:14:19.238 --> 00:14:22.298
pro-tumorigenic genes to accelerate cancer development?

236
00:14:23.288 --> 00:14:26.438
And so to address this question, we took a two-pronged approach.

237
00:14:27.158 --> 00:14:30.758
We first took the partially open chromatin regions in our ATAC-seq

238
00:14:30.838 --> 00:14:34.618
data and performed enrichment analysis for transcription factor binding

239
00:14:34.738 --> 00:14:38.318
sites as well as motif sequences. And that immediately

240
00:14:38.358 --> 00:14:42.278
revealed the enrichment of AP1 JunFos factors with

241
00:14:42.288 --> 00:14:46.218
examples like c-Jun, JunD, and Fosl2.

242
00:14:46.258 --> 00:14:49.478
And in parallel, we also looked at the expression of these JunFos

243
00:14:49.578 --> 00:14:53.338
factors by performing immunohistochemistry staining of

244
00:14:53.358 --> 00:14:56.998
breast tumor tissues and normal tissues in our mouse models.

245
00:14:57.578 --> 00:15:01.368
And we saw that across the board overall, there is an increased

246
00:15:01.418 --> 00:15:03.758
expression pattern of these JunFos factors.

247
00:15:04.218 --> 00:15:07.878
But this is most striking in the AP1 members c-Jun,

248
00:15:08.318 --> 00:15:11.898
which shows the highest level of expression in

249
00:15:11.938 --> 00:15:15.508
the early malignant cells, such as the hypoplastic

250
00:15:15.558 --> 00:15:19.258
regions, as well as the more well-differentiated early tumor

251
00:15:19.338 --> 00:15:23.218
regions, suggesting that Jun can play a particular role in the early stage

252
00:15:23.278 --> 00:15:24.267
of cancer development.

253
00:15:25.658 --> 00:15:29.258
And so further interrogating the role of AP1 in tumor

254
00:15:29.278 --> 00:15:33.018
formation, I made a new lentiviral construct that allows us to

255
00:15:33.098 --> 00:15:36.938
partially inhibit the AP1 pathway by overexpressing

256
00:15:36.998 --> 00:15:40.858
a dominant negative isoform of Jun that lacks the N-terminal

257
00:15:40.898 --> 00:15:44.858
transactivation domain, and therefore it can block the function of

258
00:15:44.898 --> 00:15:48.658
endogenous JunFos factors. And interestingly, when we

259
00:15:48.718 --> 00:15:52.598
injected this lentivirus into the wild type and heterozygous mice that I

260
00:15:52.638 --> 00:15:56.138
described earlier, we saw that this partial AP1

261
00:15:56.178 --> 00:16:00.038
inhibition can delay tumor formation in the heterozygous background,

262
00:16:00.518 --> 00:16:04.158
but didn't have an effect on the wild-type background, suggesting that the

263
00:16:04.218 --> 00:16:07.958
heterozygous mice are more dependent on the AP1 pathway

264
00:16:08.038 --> 00:16:08.278
for

265
00:16:09.118 --> 00:16:12.718
early tumor onset. And this is consistent with our

266
00:16:13.318 --> 00:16:17.078
ATAC-seq data showing that the AP1 binding sites are more

267
00:16:17.118 --> 00:16:19.038
accessible in the heterozygous state.

268
00:16:20.858 --> 00:16:24.638
And so having found AP1, we next asked a question, what

269
00:16:24.758 --> 00:16:28.458
genes associated with these AP1 bound open chromatin

270
00:16:28.538 --> 00:16:28.838
sites

271
00:16:29.638 --> 00:16:32.358
can play a role in promoting cancer development?

272
00:16:32.898 --> 00:16:36.418
And here the gene Wnt10a really caught our attention for many reasons,

273
00:16:36.918 --> 00:16:40.798
including its prominent increase in chromatin accessibility in our

274
00:16:40.897 --> 00:16:44.398
Group2 heterozygous AV cells, as well as substantially

275
00:16:44.538 --> 00:16:48.118
elevated expression of Wnt10a in the tumor samples

276
00:16:48.438 --> 00:16:50.098
compared to normal AV cells.

277
00:16:50.978 --> 00:16:54.558
Additionally, there is presence of multiple Jun binding sites in the

278
00:16:54.578 --> 00:16:58.078
Wnt10a locus, both in the mouse and human genomes,

279
00:16:58.778 --> 00:17:01.818
and that's conserved across multiple cell types.

280
00:17:02.668 --> 00:17:06.358
Additionally, there is indication of active Wnt signaling in the tumor

281
00:17:06.439 --> 00:17:10.328
cells based on expression of Wnt receptors, as well as

282
00:17:10.338 --> 00:17:13.939
downstream Wnt target genes. And finally, there is a

283
00:17:14.058 --> 00:17:17.498
strong association between Wnt10a and human breast cancer,

284
00:17:17.979 --> 00:17:21.518
specifically the basal-like breast cancer subtype relative to the other

285
00:17:21.618 --> 00:17:25.278
subtypes based on analysis of human breast tissues as well as

286
00:17:25.778 --> 00:17:26.979
patient-derived cell lines.

287
00:17:28.258 --> 00:17:30.678
And so despite all these interesting

288
00:17:31.478 --> 00:17:35.268
associations, not much was known about Wnt10a and breast cancer at the

289
00:17:35.318 --> 00:17:39.258
time. And so we set off to study the role of Wnt10a

290
00:17:39.318 --> 00:17:43.138
using our model systems, first by using tumor

291
00:17:43.148 --> 00:17:45.558
organoids derived from our mouse models.

292
00:17:46.078 --> 00:17:46.638
And that was

293
00:17:47.618 --> 00:17:51.538
done by Alyssa Cordes, who is in the audience here, and

294
00:17:52.418 --> 00:17:56.407
a very talented technician that is now a graduate student at UT Southwestern.

295
00:17:56.938 --> 00:18:00.478
And so what Alyssa found was that if she took tumor organoids and knocked down

296
00:18:00.498 --> 00:18:03.698
Wnt10a using different short hairpins, we're

297
00:18:04.338 --> 00:18:07.838
able to see that now these tumor organoids have substantially

298
00:18:07.898 --> 00:18:11.478
dampened Wnt signaling based on expression of downstream

299
00:18:11.558 --> 00:18:15.258
genes like Axin2 and Tcf7l2. And now

300
00:18:15.298 --> 00:18:18.968
these tumor organoids with Wnt10a knockdown have

301
00:18:18.978 --> 00:18:22.818
substantially impaired ability to grow as tumor spheres in culture,

302
00:18:23.618 --> 00:18:27.118
as well as to grow as transplant tumors in mice,

303
00:18:27.538 --> 00:18:31.198
suggesting that Wnt10a is required to maintain the fitness of these

304
00:18:31.238 --> 00:18:34.894
cancer cells.Additionally, when we overexpress

305
00:18:34.914 --> 00:18:38.874
WNT10A to ask the effect on tumorigenesis in our

306
00:18:38.914 --> 00:18:42.874
mouse models, we saw that this WNT10A overexpression is sufficient

307
00:18:42.894 --> 00:18:46.534
to substantially accelerate cancer formation compared to the cohort

308
00:18:46.934 --> 00:18:50.784
and also elevate the tumor grade, suggesting that WNT10A is a potent

309
00:18:50.894 --> 00:18:53.434
driver of basal-like breast cancer development.

310
00:18:54.994 --> 00:18:58.774
So being very much encouraged by our discovery of the role of

311
00:18:59.054 --> 00:19:02.934
AP1 and also WNT10A using our approach, we then

312
00:19:03.094 --> 00:19:06.654
applied the same approach to look for other transcription factors that are

313
00:19:07.274 --> 00:19:09.614
revealed by this chromatin priming mechanism.

314
00:19:10.154 --> 00:19:13.734
And that brought our attention to the RUNX family as well as the CBFB

315
00:19:13.834 --> 00:19:17.494
cofactor, and that's an independent project led by Isabella

316
00:19:17.574 --> 00:19:18.634
Kecno in my lab.

317
00:19:19.534 --> 00:19:23.094
And so we found that these partially open chromatin regions that I

318
00:19:23.104 --> 00:19:26.474
described earlier in the ATAC-seq data are substantially

319
00:19:26.514 --> 00:19:30.384
enriched for RUNX binding sites as well as motif sequences.

320
00:19:31.034 --> 00:19:34.994
And when we looked at the expression level of the RUNX and CBFB

321
00:19:35.094 --> 00:19:38.604
factors now using single-cell RNA sequencing, we saw

322
00:19:38.654 --> 00:19:42.534
that compared to the normal AV cells in both a

323
00:19:42.554 --> 00:19:45.814
wild-type or heterozygous background at young age or older age,

324
00:19:46.334 --> 00:19:46.594
the

325
00:19:47.574 --> 00:19:50.954
basal-like breast cancer tumors arising in either a wild-type or

326
00:19:51.014 --> 00:19:54.354
heterozygous background have substantially elevated expression of

327
00:19:54.414 --> 00:19:58.004
CBFB and RUNX1, and to a lesser extent, also

328
00:19:58.034 --> 00:19:59.214
RUNX2 and RUNX3.

329
00:20:00.694 --> 00:20:04.474
And to further look at the expression of these factors specifically

330
00:20:04.514 --> 00:20:07.814
now in the pre-malignant state, Mayura Thomas, another

331
00:20:08.254 --> 00:20:11.994
talented technician, developed an organoid

332
00:20:12.054 --> 00:20:15.834
model for pre-malignant cells that allowed us to

333
00:20:15.914 --> 00:20:19.714
culture normal AV cells derived from either wild-type or

334
00:20:19.754 --> 00:20:22.824
heterozygous mice, and then be acutely treated with

335
00:20:22.854 --> 00:20:26.614
lentiCRE to delete BRCA1 and p53.

336
00:20:27.374 --> 00:20:31.064
And we found that this pre-malignant model showed us

337
00:20:31.114 --> 00:20:34.944
that very quickly the pre-malignant cells, upon loss of BRCA1 and

338
00:20:34.974 --> 00:20:38.854
p53, elevates the expression of CBFB, and

339
00:20:38.914 --> 00:20:42.754
to an even greater extent, RUNX2, suggesting that these factors can

340
00:20:42.794 --> 00:20:45.914
play a role in the very stage of transformation.

341
00:20:47.314 --> 00:20:50.734
So to interrogate the functional effects of these RUNX and CBFB

342
00:20:50.854 --> 00:20:54.454
factors, Isabella did functional analysis by

343
00:20:54.514 --> 00:20:57.994
taking cancer cell lines derived from our mouse models and knocked

344
00:20:58.074 --> 00:21:01.714
down these factors using short hairpins, and

345
00:21:02.014 --> 00:21:05.314
then look at the effect on cell proliferation by live-cell imaging.

346
00:21:05.964 --> 00:21:09.854
And that showed us that interestingly, knockdown of CBFB

347
00:21:09.914 --> 00:21:13.634
and RUNX2 substantially delayed the proliferation or

348
00:21:13.674 --> 00:21:17.634
inhibited proliferation of these cells, shown here both as a time

349
00:21:17.694 --> 00:21:21.614
course of the five-day proliferation as well as the endpoint confluency.

350
00:21:22.214 --> 00:21:25.594
And this is representative of multiple experiments that we have done to

351
00:21:25.634 --> 00:21:29.604
date. This effect of CBFB and RUNX2 is in

352
00:21:29.654 --> 00:21:33.314
contrast to the knockdown of RUNX1 and RUNX3, which didn't

353
00:21:33.354 --> 00:21:37.334
inhibit proliferation. And if anything, RUNX3 knockdown

354
00:21:37.434 --> 00:21:40.274
actually seemed to promote proliferation of these cancer cells.

355
00:21:41.734 --> 00:21:45.714
And so Isabella is now actively studying the effect of these factors in

356
00:21:46.034 --> 00:21:49.854
regulating tumorigenesis in our mouse models, and also

357
00:21:49.974 --> 00:21:52.634
identifying the transcription targets by

358
00:21:53.534 --> 00:21:55.934
performing RNA-seq and cut-and-run analysis.

359
00:21:56.434 --> 00:22:00.424
We're also studying the relevance of these RUNX and CBFB factors to

360
00:22:00.494 --> 00:22:04.304
human basal-like breast cancer by analyzing tissues and performing in

361
00:22:04.334 --> 00:22:05.554
vitro functional studies.

362
00:22:07.214 --> 00:22:08.564
So beyond these

363
00:22:09.694 --> 00:22:13.674
transcription factor programs that I have outlined to you today, our lab is

364
00:22:13.754 --> 00:22:17.714
also actively studying other aspects of this chromatin priming mechanism

365
00:22:18.154 --> 00:22:22.134
that I don't have time to go into details right now, but I'm very happy to talk

366
00:22:22.194 --> 00:22:25.924
more about offline. And this includes the mechanisms that

367
00:22:26.074 --> 00:22:29.634
drives the chromatin remodeling process, specifically in the

368
00:22:29.694 --> 00:22:32.834
heterozygous alveolar cells, and how this

369
00:22:34.154 --> 00:22:37.924
chromatin accessibility change relates to and impacts the

370
00:22:37.974 --> 00:22:41.164
tissue and cell type specificity that we see in

371
00:22:41.194 --> 00:22:43.374
BRCA1 hereditary breast cancer.

372
00:22:44.234 --> 00:22:48.094
Additionally, we study how these chromatin changes interact with

373
00:22:48.154 --> 00:22:51.494
physiological stress factors like pregnancy and aging and

374
00:22:51.634 --> 00:22:55.074
obesity that can substantially impact breast cancer risks.

375
00:22:55.594 --> 00:22:59.514
And we think that the insights gained from these studies

376
00:22:59.554 --> 00:23:03.334
can help us develop better strategies for risk assessment and

377
00:23:03.414 --> 00:23:06.854
also early intervention, not only in the hereditary cancer setting,

378
00:23:07.254 --> 00:23:10.634
but also in the sporadic cancer setting, given the high molecular

379
00:23:10.754 --> 00:23:13.494
similarities between the two forms of the same disease.

380
00:23:14.774 --> 00:23:18.514
And so there are many exciting directions that we're pursuing in the lab.

381
00:23:18.994 --> 00:23:22.964
And with that, I'll stop here and thank all the people who contributed to

382
00:23:22.994 --> 00:23:26.934
this work, especially my former mentor, Zheng, and

383
00:23:26.994 --> 00:23:30.894
her whole lab, and with a special shout-out to many talented

384
00:23:30.904 --> 00:23:33.654
technicians and undergraduate students who've worked with me.

385
00:23:34.084 --> 00:23:37.774
And I'll also highlight our wonderful collaborators and our sources of funding.

386
00:23:38.514 --> 00:23:42.434
And in my new lab, I'm very much excited about the active ongoing

387
00:23:42.474 --> 00:23:46.194
work, and I'm a proud member of the cancer research community at

388
00:23:46.274 --> 00:23:50.174
Penn, including the Department of Cancer Biology, the Baser

389
00:23:50.234 --> 00:23:52.894
Center for BRCA, and the Abramson Cancer Center.

390
00:23:53.354 --> 00:23:56.034
And I see some of the members represented in the audience here.

391
00:23:56.114 --> 00:23:56.894
Thank you for coming.

392
00:23:57.734 --> 00:24:01.214
I'm grateful for the support of AACR, as well as other

393
00:24:01.254 --> 00:24:04.034
foundations like the ACS and the Breakthrough Challenge Foundation.

394
00:24:04.614 --> 00:24:08.414
As a new lab, we're very much open to feedback, and we're very much open to

395
00:24:08.534 --> 00:24:11.694
forming new collaborations. So please don't hesitate to reach out.

396
00:24:12.184 --> 00:24:15.314
And we're actively recruiting new lab members at all levels.

397
00:24:15.634 --> 00:24:19.134
So if you're interested in finding out more, I'm happy to chat

398
00:24:19.194 --> 00:24:22.734
anytime. And here are my contact information and lab website.

399
00:24:23.174 --> 00:24:26.934
So I thank everyone for your attention and happy to take questions.

400
00:24:40.806 --> 00:24:44.506
I maybe can start with one. I can see a couple of people

401
00:24:44.586 --> 00:24:48.066
lining up. But I do have a couple of maybe

402
00:24:48.126 --> 00:24:52.026
connected question on translation ability of the data that it's the

403
00:24:52.066 --> 00:24:55.386
very elegant study that you published, and it was very well done.

404
00:24:55.926 --> 00:24:59.636
And you hint a little bit about it, the next step, and how these

405
00:24:59.706 --> 00:25:02.906
translate to human breast cancer.

406
00:25:03.666 --> 00:25:07.656
So I was thinking, what's your opinion about it, the mouse model

407
00:25:07.706 --> 00:25:11.006
that you generated, how translationable that is based on

408
00:25:11.446 --> 00:25:15.406
human breast cancer, and as well as you believe that some of the

409
00:25:15.446 --> 00:25:19.406
finding can later on lead to maybe early prediction

410
00:25:19.446 --> 00:25:23.226
or even treatment of hereditary breast cancer.

411
00:25:24.286 --> 00:25:25.886
Yeah, I think that those are good questions.

412
00:25:25.966 --> 00:25:26.146
So,

413
00:25:27.066 --> 00:25:30.906
in terms of what you're asking about the translatability to

414
00:25:30.966 --> 00:25:34.646
human breast cancer, hereditary breast cancer, we're actively studying on that.

415
00:25:35.366 --> 00:25:39.226
It's a great question. It's not an easy question to answer given the wide

416
00:25:39.266 --> 00:25:41.506
degree of heterogeneity in patient tissues.

417
00:25:41.966 --> 00:25:42.246
And,

418
00:25:43.366 --> 00:25:47.266
one important aspect for this kind of analysis is also to account for all the

419
00:25:47.346 --> 00:25:51.306
other confounding variables, such as the effect of age, the history of

420
00:25:51.366 --> 00:25:55.246
pregnancy, the menopausal state, the hormonal state,

421
00:25:55.646 --> 00:25:58.546
which could be challenging to account for and

422
00:26:00.966 --> 00:26:03.346
in contrast to what we can do in the mouse model.

423
00:26:03.726 --> 00:26:07.586
But I think this is a very important question, and we're actively working on that.

424
00:26:08.106 --> 00:26:09.686
And in terms of identifying

425
00:26:10.506 --> 00:26:13.886
patients that can benefit from this kind of

426
00:26:14.606 --> 00:26:18.406
mechanistic insight, I think this is another question that we're

