00:27:26.786 --> 00:27:30.246
positive. In our mouse model, we actually are able to capture that.

448
00:27:30.566 --> 00:27:34.286
So there is a small fraction that does express hormone

449
00:27:34.326 --> 00:27:35.606
receptors and

450
00:27:36.566 --> 00:27:40.546
do not fully reflect a basal type. And this also is an opportunity

451
00:27:40.586 --> 00:27:43.806
that we're very well aware of and very much interested in

452
00:27:44.006 --> 00:27:44.606
pursuing

453
00:27:45.526 --> 00:27:48.566
how these different subtypes of breast cancer

454
00:27:49.326 --> 00:27:51.286
are regulated and

455
00:27:57.166 --> 00:27:59.546
what's the underlying mechanism of driving that.

456
00:27:59.766 --> 00:28:03.186
And I think we have very good tools to look into those questions.

457
00:28:04.646 --> 00:28:04.826
Yeah.

458
00:28:05.806 --> 00:28:07.526
All right. That's a very interesting talk.

459
00:28:08.646 --> 00:28:11.906
I'm just curious that you show some transcription factors that their

460
00:28:13.246 --> 00:28:16.686
levels were increased in the premalignant state.

461
00:28:16.966 --> 00:28:17.186
Mm-hmm.

462
00:28:19.806 --> 00:28:23.106
What's the reason for their level being increased in that state?

463
00:28:23.466 --> 00:28:26.986
Is there any thought? What drive their upregulation in the

464
00:28:27.026 --> 00:28:27.906
premalignant state?

465
00:28:28.155 --> 00:28:28.155
Yeah.

466
00:28:28.166 --> 00:28:29.296
That's one. Second is that-

467
00:28:29.326 --> 00:28:29.866
Yeah

468
00:28:29.875 --> 00:28:33.586
... are some of the transcription factors themself causal if you don't have the

469
00:28:33.666 --> 00:28:37.286
genetic change and just make them slightly

